            "text": "ROOT",
            "relation": "null"
        },
        {
            "id": 1,
            "parent": 2,
            "text": "Taken abstractly , ",
            "relation": "CONDITION"
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "the two-level ( Kimmo ) morphological framework allows computationally difficult problems to arise . <S>",
            "relation": "CONTRAST"
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "parent": 2,
            "text": "For example , N + 1 small automata are sufficient to encode the Boolean satisfiability problem ( SAT ) for formulas in N variables . <S>",
            "relation": "EXEMPLIFICATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "However , the suspicion arises ",
            "relation": "ATTRIBUTION"
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "that natural-language problems may have a special structure ",
            "relation": "BACKGROUND"
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "-- not shared with SAT -- ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "that is not directly captured in the two-level model . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "In particular , the natural problems may generally have a modular and local nature ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "parent": 8,
            "text": "that distinguishes them from more \" global \" SAT problems . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "By exploiting this structure , ",
            "relation": "MANNER-MEANS"
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "parent": 0,
            "text": "it may be possible to solve the natural problems by methods ",
            "relation": "ROOT"
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "that do not involve combinatorial search . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "We have explored this possibility in a preliminary way ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 14,
            "parent": 13,
            "text": "by applying constraint propagation methods to Kimmo generation and recognition . <S>",
            "relation": "MANNER-MEANS"
        },
        {
            "id": 15,
            "parent": 17,
            "text": "Constraint propagation can succeed ",
            "relation": "CONTRAST"
        },
        {
            "id": 16,
            "parent": 15,
            "text": "when the solution falls into place step-by-step through a chain of limited and local inferences , ",
            "relation": "CONDITION"
        },
        {
            "id": 17,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "but it is insufficiently powerful to solve unnaturally hard SAT problems . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 18,
            "parent": 19,
            "text": "Limited tests indicate ",
            "relation": "ATTRIBUTION"
        },
        {
            "id": 19,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "that the constraint-propagation algorithm for Kimmo generation works for English , Turkish , and Warlpiri . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 20,
            "parent": 22,
            "text": "When applied to a Kimmo system ",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT-REASON"
        },
        {
            "id": 21,
            "parent": 20,
            "text": "that encodes SAT problems , ",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 22,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "the algorithm succeeds on \" easy \" SAT problems ",
            "relation": "EVALUATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 23,
            "parent": 22,
            "text": "but fails ( as desired ) on \" hard \" problems . <S>  ",
            "relation": "CONTRAST"
        }
    ]
}